The concept of enzyme was first proposed by Wilhelm Kühne in 1878, referring to a class of biocatalysts with high catalytic efficiency and strong selectivity [25]. They are widely used in food, medical and petroleum industries due to their high catalytic efficiency and selectivity. However, their limitations, such as poor stability, volatility, one-time use restrictions, recycling difficulties, high costs, and the challenges of continuous production have prompted scientists to seek alternatives (
                     Table 1) [26]. The study of mimetic enzymes began in 1965, followed by the discovery of molecularly imprinted polymerases, antibodies, and DNAzymes [27,28]. But the molecular structure of these traditional mimics limits their ability to accurately replicate the complex structure of natural enzymes, resulting in their catalytic activity usually not comparable to that of natural enzymes [29–31]. The development of mimetic enzymes with stronger biocatalytic properties has become a key goal of scientific research. In 1987, Haruta et al. [32] found that when gold particles were as small as 2–5 nm, they could efficiently catalyze the oxidation of carbon monoxide at extremely low temperatures (as low as −70 °C). This finding not only has a milestone significance in catalytic science but also provides a new direction for the subsequent research of nanomaterials, especially in the simulation of the catalytic properties of biological enzymes. Based on Haruta's work, in 1990, researchers found that specific nanomaterials had catalytic properties similar to enzymes [33]. This discovery has inspired scientists to explore the high specific surface area and excellent catalytic performance of nanomaterials, and prompted them to think about how to transfer enzyme activity to the nanoscale, which marks the beginning of the study of nanomaterials with enzyme activity. In 1993, Tokuyama et al. [34] reported the breakthrough discovery of fullerene derivatives mimicking the function of DNA restriction endonuclease. In 1997, fullerenes and their derivatives were confirmed to have superoxide dismutase (SOD) activity, marking the first discovery of inorganic nanomolecules with enzyme activity [35]. In 2004, Scrimin, Pasquato et al. [36] first proposed the concept of “nanozyme”. In this study, azacrown was modified on the surface of gold nanoparticles (NPs) and chelated with zinc ions to obtain catalytic activity for cleavage of phosphate diester bonds, thus simulating the function of ribonuclease. The catalytic activity of the modified gold nanoparticles mainly comes from the surface modified chemicals, rather than the inherent properties of the nanomaterials. In 2007, Yan et al. [37] first reported the intrinsic peroxidase-like (POD-like) activity of Fe3O4 NPs, which marked the official start of the field of nanozymes. Although the term “nanozyme” is not used in this study, it has been clearly stated that nanoparticles have “intrinsic peroxidase-like activity”. In 2008, the team of Wang Erkang developed a new method for the detection of glucose by using the POD-like activity of Fe3O4 [38]. Subsequently, many scientists around the world have reported that other nanomaterials also exhibit enzyme-like catalytic activity, further confirming that the enzyme-like catalytic properties of nanomaterials are a common phenomenon [39]. How to define such nanomaterials with unique catalytic properties has gradually become a major challenge in the research field. In 2013, Wei and Wang first proposed the formal definition of nanozyme: “nanomaterial with enzyme-like characteristics” [40]. Since then, this definition and its variants (e.g., catalytically active nanomaterials or nanomaterials-based artificial enzymes) have frequently appeared in the relevant literature [41,42]. The proposal of this definition has greatly promoted the exploration of new nanomaterials for catalytic biological reactions and prompted people to find more potential substrates for existing catalytic nanomaterials. In recent years, with the deepening of nanozyme research and the strengthening of interdisciplinary integration, there is an urgent need for a clearer and more widely accepted definition to standardize this emerging field. In 2021, Wei et al. [43] proposed an updated definition of nanozymes: “nanomaterials that catalyze the conversion of enzyme substrates to products and follow enzymatic kinetics (e.g., Michaelis–Menten) under physiologically relevant conditions, even though the molecular mechanisms of the reactions could be different between nanozymes and the corresponding enzymes” which acknowledged potential mechanistic differences between nanozymes and enzymes and emphasized the functional aspect. In 2022, nanozymes were recognized by the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) as one of the top ten emerging chemical technologies, reflecting their significant impact and potential [44]. Driven by global scientific communities spanning chemistry, enzymology, materials science, biology, medicine, and theoretical computation, the annual publication count in the core nanozyme field has surged past 1600, with a notable increase observed in the past five years. The exponential growth in publications and citations has solidified nanozymes research as a distinct field. B. Das et al. [45] offer an exhaustive historical account of nanozymes evolution (Fig. 1
                     ).
